		"body": "Problem\r\nWhen importing .one or .onepkg files into Joplin, users occasionally encounter hard crashes or failed imports if the OneNote file contains unrecognized data forms or complex structures not fully supported by the parser yet. For example, paragraphs combining both regular text and embedded objects cause immediate app panics, preventing the import of the entire notebook. Furthermore, the handling of trailing slashes and backslashes during path parsing is unstable on Windows, generating duplicated paths that trigger directory creation errors and completely halt the import process.\r\n\r\nSolution\r\nThe importer has been modified to gracefully handle unsupported elements and structural mismatches instead of panicking. Encountering an unparseable embedded object, table structure, or unexpected datatype now generates an error or a log warning, allowing the system to safely bypass the failing element and continue successfully importing the rest of the valid notes. Additionally, the path generation logic was refactored to cleanly iterate paths by characters instead of raw byte indexes, repairing the path concatenation bugs blocking Windows users from importing notes.\r\n\r\nTest Plan\r\nManually verified that Joplin successfully imports test .one and .onepkg files containing edge cases and previously crashing structures (such as malformed tables and mixed paragraphs) while gracefully logging warnings.\r\nRan the full InteropService test suite (\r\nInteropService_Importer_OneNote.test.ts\r\n), verifying all existing OneNote notebook layouts continue to parse and deserialize without regression.\r\nExtended the \r\napi.rs\r\n parser-utils tests with a new module validating the Windows file-path normalization fixes across case-insensitive and multibyte character path edge-cases.",
